    "explanation": "たがる (tagaru) is for third person use only. If you want to say that “you” personally want to do something, use ～たい (tai) instead.たがる (tagaru) stems from がる (garu), which expresses that someone “appears to be ~”.Example A) General Use友達が留学したがる。tomodachi ga ryuugaku shi tagaru.My friend wants to study abroad (in general).Example B) Current form友達が留学したがっている。tomodachi ga ryuugaku shi tagatteiru.My friend is wanting to study abroad.Example C) Past form友達が留学したがった。tomodachi ga ryuugaku shi tagatta.My friend wanted to study abroad.Example D) Negative form友達が留学したがらない。tomodachi ga ryuugaku shi tagaranai.My friend does not want to study abroad.Other ways to express wanting somethingWant someone to do something: use てほしい (te hoshii).I want to do something: use ～たい (tai).Want something: use がほしい (ga ...",
